g.text: Ringmerking.no - a birdlife service for birdlovers.

text.tspan: Re-design the service to make it mobile-first, user-friendly, usable, and
desirable. The service should make it easier to register a bird sighting,
be engaged in its use, and respect the current users of the service who
were well accustomed to the current practice and use.
Our team followed the design sprint process to solve a problem quickly. We started by analyzing the problem and gathering feedback from expert users to
create personas. During the ideation phase, we brainstormed potential solutions and selected a feature to focus on - the bird sighting registration process. We
made decisions through a rapid ideation and sketching session, and once we had decided on an idea, we created a lo-fi Figma prototype to test it. The prot
type was tested in-house with a diverse group of participants, and we made iterative changes based on their feedback. In the end, we derived a more extensive
user flow for the bird sighting registration process. Overall, the design sprint process was an efficient and effective way to solve our problem and create a
solution in a short amount of time.
The biggest design challenge we encountered was the myriad of colors of the bird ID rings that had to be implemented into the app. Distinguishing these from one another
could be the difference between a correct registration and a misregistration. The 15 different colors of the rings influenced our color palette for the app in that this would
now be more restrictive due to the many swatches.
The project itself was created by Sabima, a Norwegian organization for wildlife and nature conservation and protection. Sabima
is engaged with several projects around in Norway and fights eagerly to preserve the biological diversity that is slowly being
eradicated in Norwegian nature
The Ringmerking.no service is created and maintained by both BirdLife Norge and Stavanger Museum, these were the two other
stakeholders of this project. BirdLife Norge is a Norwegian ornithological association that works for protecting birds in Norway
and has over 10.000 members. Stavanger Museum is organizing ring registration (unique ID rings uses to identify the birds) of all
birds in Norway and is maintaining the existing Ringmerking.no service. In their database, they have over 9 million registered
birds that they keep information on regarding habitat, hatching, and travel route.
How do we give life to an old birdlife registration
service to attract new users, increase user adop
tion, and ultimately lead to higher rates of bird
registrations?
A completely new makeover of the birdlife service which is designed for mobile-first. A easy to use bird sighting registration flow.
A simple profile overview with a listing of your bird sightings as well as favorites. A specific page about each bird species contai
ing species information, types of possible, color-ID rings, avs well as aesthetical characteristics of the bird.
